subSubSection.paragraph:
Abdomen
/ 
Male terminalia
(
Fig. 8
). Tergites predominantly yellow with yellow gray pruinosity. Syntergite 1+2 uniformly yellow; tergites 3–5 each with 2 pairs of large paired brown pruinose spots dorsally, encompassing anterior edges of tergites; covered by dark setulae slightly longer at posterior margin of each one. Tergite 6 (
Figs 9–11
) sclerotized, about 6X wider than long, bare. Sternite 6 asymmetrical, strongly connected laterally to syntergosternite 7+8. Syntergosternite 7+8 (
Figs 9–11
) sclerotized, asymmetrical, triangular, right-sided vertex, almost completely offset to the left, bare. Epandrium subglobose, with appearance of an arc, anterior ½ bare, setulose in posterior ½, wider than long; with posterior margin raised in the middle, where vertical cerci are inserted. Surstylus fixed to epandrium, but with a clear point of weakness, appearing as being articulated. Cercus small, setulose and directed to below.
